```json
{
  "project_name": "student-profile-system",
  "description": "GOAL: Build a modern, responsive full-stack Student Profile Management System — a single polished dark-themed dashboard where a school user can view, search, add, edit, and delete student records (Student ID, Full Name, Email, Major, GPA) with real persistence. Why: the request asks for the four CRUD flows plus a beautiful, modern, responsive UI over a local database.\n\nSTACK & LAYOUT: Next.js 14 (App Router) + React 18 in TypeScript (strict); TailwindCSS v3; Prisma ORM over local SQLite; lucide-react icons; Vitest tests. A src/ package layout is genuinely required by App Router. Path alias '@/*' -> './src/*' in both tsconfig and vitest. Do NOT add auth, pagination, request-size limits, extra abstractions, or files beyond those listed.\n\nGLOBAL CONVENTIONS (state once here, referenced by file specs):\n- CLIENT STUDENT SHAPE (declared locally in each client component that needs it): { id: number; studentId: string; fullName: string; email: string; major: string; gpa: number; createdAt: string; updatedAt: string }. createdAt/updatedAt are ISO strings because the server serializes Prisma DateTime with toISOString() before crossing the server/client boundary.\n- VALIDATION SOURCE OF TRUTH: all field rules and their exact English messages live only in src/lib/validation.ts; the client form and both API routes import and reuse them so they can never drift. Do not restate messages elsewhere.\n- API STATUS CONTRACT (authoritative): GET /api/students -> 200 (array, newest first). POST /api/students -> 201 valid; 400 {errors} invalid fields; 400 {error:'Invalid JSON'} malformed body; 409 {errors:{studentId: DUPLICATE_MESSAGE}} on Prisma P2002; 500 {error:'Internal server error'} otherwise. PATCH /api/students/[id] -> 200 valid; 400 invalid fields; 400 Invalid JSON; 404 {error:'Not found'} for a bad id or Prisma P2025; 409 duplicate (P2002); 500 otherwise. DELETE /api/students/[id] -> 204 (empty body) valid; 404 for bad id or P2025; 500 otherwise. DUPLICATE_MESSAGE is exactly 'A student with this Student ID already exists'.\n- SEMANTIC CHOICES (chosen deliberately, honored by the algorithms): (a) text length caps use JavaScript String.length (UTF-16 code units) after trimming — ASCII-pragmatic, NOT grapheme/full-Unicode counting; (b) email uses the pragmatic HTML5-style regex ^[^\\s@]+@[^\\s@]+\\.[^\\s@]+$ — NOT full RFC 5322; (c) GPA is accepted only as a plain decimal numeral matching ^-?\\d+(\\.\\d+)?$ (rejects 0x3, 0b11, 1e0, abc), constrained to the closed interval [0.0, 4.0], stored as Float/REAL; (d) client search is a case-insensitive substring match using String.prototype.toLowerCase() (ASCII-pragmatic, no locale/Unicode casefold) over fullName, major, and studentId against the trimmed+lowercased query, empty query shows all; (e) GPA color thresholds use inclusive lower bounds: >=3.5 emerald, >=2.5 amber, else rose; (f) the item route id path segment must match ^\\d+$, be at most 15 digits, and resolve via Number() to a positive safe integer, otherwise it is a non-enumerating 404 (this rejects 0, negatives, decimals, hex, and exponent forms); (g) summary metrics are computed over the FULL dataset independent of the search filter — narrowing the list never changes the headline numbers; (h) average GPA = mean rounded via Math.round(x*100)/100 then toFixed(2), '—' for an empty list; (i) top major = highest count via a Map preserving insertion order, ties broken by first-seen, '—' for an empty list.\n- MODAL A11Y CONVENTIONS (StudentForm dialog and DeleteDialog alertdialog): the parent mounts each dialog only while open; on open move focus to the safe default control (StudentForm: the first field / Student ID input; DeleteDialog: the Cancel button); trap Tab/Shift+Tab wrapping at BOTH ends using the shared FOCUSABLE_SELECTOR scoped to the panel; Escape closes (preventDefault then the close callback); a mouse interaction on the backdrop overlay itself (target === currentTarget), not the panel, closes; on unmount restore focus to whatever element was focused when the dialog mounted (guard it is still connected); panels use role dialog / alertdialog with aria-modal='true' and aria-labelledby (plus aria-describedby for delete). FOCUSABLE_SELECTOR is exactly the joined set: a[href], button:not([disabled]), input:not([disabled]), select, textarea, [tabindex]:not([tabindex=\"-1\"]).\n- CONTROL CONVENTIONS: interactive controls have a >=48px minimum touch target and a visible :focus-visible ring (global fallback box-shadow in globals.css plus local Tailwind focus-visible ring utilities); form controls use font-size >=1rem (16px) so iOS never zooms on focus.\n- THEME TOKENS: deep navy/slate fixed gradient background with light text; a reusable frosted-glass .card surface; a brand color ramp; Inter (font-sans) + Outfit (font-display) loaded via next/font as CSS variables; emerald/amber/rose accents; a staggered fade-in-up entrance animation.\n\nMUST NOT CHANGE / SECURITY: never create, read, parse, or echo any .env file or secret value — the Prisma datasource url is a hardcoded literal 'file:./dev.db' (NOT an env() reference) and must stay that way. Do not hand-edit next-env.d.ts or prisma/migrations/migration_lock.toml. Do not alter the exact validation messages or the status-code contract (they are locked by tests).\n\nTEST STRATEGY: Vitest with three surfaces across two environments. (1) node — src/lib/validation.test.ts locks every validator's exact return value/message and boundaries. (2) node — src/app/api/students/route.test.ts drives the exported GET/POST/PATCH/DELETE handlers against a vi.mock('@/lib/prisma') client to lock the full 200/201/400/409/404/204 contract with no database. (3) jsdom — src/components/*.dom.test.tsx drive StudentForm and DeleteDialog with Testing Library + user-event to lock the hand-written a11y behaviors. Presentational styling is verified at compile time by npm run build (type-check + bundle) and npm run lint.\n\nDONE-WHEN: (1) npm install, npx prisma generate, npx prisma db push (creates prisma/dev.db + the Student table), and npm run db:seed (idempotent) all succeed. (2) npm run build passes (prisma generate + next build: type-check + production bundle). (3) npm run lint passes. (4) npm run test (vitest run) passes all three surfaces. (5) Behaviors hold: dashboard lists students newest-first as cards with a color-coded GPA; summary cards show total, average GPA, and top major over the full dataset; the search box filters the visible cards by name/major/id case-insensitively while metrics stay put; the Add modal creates via POST and refreshes; Edit updates via PATCH; Delete confirms and removes via DELETE; a duplicate Student ID surfaces an inline 409 field error on the form; invalid fields surface inline 400 errors; an empty database shows the empty state and an empty search result shows the no-match state.\n\nAssumptions: The user stated only Next.js App Router + TailwindCSS + local SQLite (Prisma or mock) + the four CRUD flows + a beautiful/modern/responsive UI. Everything else is an introduced design decision a reviewer may trim: choosing Prisma+SQLite over mock storage; the specific field constraints, messages, and status-code contract; the ASCII-pragmatic email/length/search/GPA semantics; the modal a11y behaviors and focus management; the summary-metrics-over-full-dataset scope; the GPA color thresholds; the glassmorphism dark theme, fonts, and animations; the six seed students; the committed migration history; and the deliberate no-auth / no-pagination / no-body-limit scope (delegated to a deployment/proxy layer)."
  ,
  "files": [
    {
      "path": "package.json",
      "specification": "PURPOSE: npm manifest defining project metadata, scripts, and the exact dependency set. CONTENT: name 'student-profile-system', private true, \"type\": \"module\". scripts: dev = 'next dev'; build = 'prisma generate && next build'; start = 'next start'; lint = 'next lint'; test = 'vitest run'; db:push = 'prisma db push'; db:seed = 'tsx prisma/seed.ts'. dependencies: next ^14, react ^18, react-dom ^18, @prisma/client ^5, lucide-react ^0.400. devDependencies: prisma ^5, typescript ^5, @types/react ^18, @types/react-dom ^18, @types/node ^20, tailwindcss ^3, postcss ^8, autoprefixer ^10, eslint ^8, eslint-config-next ^14, vitest ^1, tsx ^4, jsdom ^24, @testing-library/react ^16, @testing-library/user-event ^14, @testing-library/jest-dom ^6. EDGE CASES: build MUST run prisma generate before next build so the Prisma client exists for the type-check. HOW TO TEST: verified implicitly by the DONE-WHEN commands (install/build/lint/test/db scripts) resolving and running."
    },
    {
      "path": "tsconfig.json",
      "specification": "PURPOSE: TypeScript configuration for a Next.js 14 App Router project. CONTENT: compilerOptions target ES2020; lib [dom, dom.iterable, esnext]; module esnext; moduleResolution 'bundler'; jsx 'preserve'; strict true; esModuleInterop true; allowJs true; skipLibCheck true; noEmit true; incremental true; resolveJsonModule true; isolatedModules true; allowSyntheticDefaultImports true; forceConsistentCasingInFileNames true; plugins [{ name: 'next' }]; paths { '@/*': ['./src/*'] }. include: next-env.d.ts, **/*.ts, **/*.tsx, .next/types/**/*.ts. exclude: node_modules. HOW TO IMPLEMENT: this is the standard create-next-app tsconfig with the '@/*' -> './src/*' alias added; the alias MUST mirror vitest.config.ts so imports resolve identically. HOW TO TEST: passing npm run build (tsc type-check via next build) is the check."
    },
    {
      "path": "next.config.mjs",
      "specification": "PURPOSE: minimal Next.js config. CONTENT: export default an empty NextConfig object (App Router is the default in 14 and no experimental flags are needed). Include the '@type {import(\\'next\\').NextConfig}' JSDoc annotation on the config const. HOW TO TEST: build succeeds with no config warnings."
    },
    {
      "path": "postcss.config.mjs",
      "specification": "PURPOSE: PostCSS pipeline for Tailwind. CONTENT: export default a config object whose plugins map enables tailwindcss ({}) and autoprefixer ({}). tailwindcss processes the @tailwind directives in globals.css; autoprefixer adds vendor prefixes. HOW TO TEST: Tailwind utility classes render after build (verified by build succeeding and the app styling)."
    },
    {
      "path": "tailwind.config.ts",
      "specification": "PURPOSE: Tailwind v3 design tokens. SIGNATURES: default-export a typed Config (import type { Config } from 'tailwindcss'; import colors from 'tailwindcss/colors'). CONTENT: content = ['./src/**/*.{ts,tsx}'] (must cover every file using a class or it is purged). theme.extend.colors: a 'brand' ramp with exact hexes 50 #f2f5fb, 100 #e2e8f4, 200 #c6d2e8, 300 #9db1d6, 400 #6d89bf, 500 #4a68a6, 600 #39518a, 700 #2f4270, 800 #2a385e, 900 #26314f, 950 #141a2e; plus emerald: colors.emerald and amber: colors.amber (reusing Tailwind's default ramps so full shades stay available). theme.extend.fontFamily: sans = ['var(--font-inter)', 'system-ui', 'sans-serif']; display = ['var(--font-outfit)', 'var(--font-inter)', 'sans-serif']. theme.extend.keyframes 'fade-in-up': 0% { opacity 0, transform translateY(8px) } to 100% { opacity 1, transform translateY(0) }. theme.extend.animation 'fade-in-up': 'fade-in-up 0.4s ease-out both'. plugins: []. EDGE CASES: the font-family entries reference the CSS variables published by next/font in layout.tsx; the brand-*/emerald-*/amber-* tokens are consumed by class names across components (e.g. brand-500, brand-900, emerald-500). HOW TO TEST: build compiles and the referenced tokens/animation resolve to real utilities."
    },
    {
      "path": "next-env.d.ts",
      "specification": "PURPOSE: Next.js-generated ambient type reference stub. CONTENT: exactly the two triple-slash reference directives — one for 'next' and one for 'next/image-types/global' — followed by the standard 'This file should not be edited' note pointing at the Next.js TypeScript docs. MUST NOT: hand-edit or add anything; Next regenerates it. HOW TO TEST: presence lets tsconfig 'include' resolve Next's types during build."
    },
    {
      "path": ".gitignore",
      "specification": "PURPOSE: keep build output, dependencies, the local database, and secrets out of version control. CONTENT: ignore /node_modules; Next output /.next and /out; the local SQLite database /prisma/dev.db and /prisma/dev.db-journal; *.log; .DS_Store; and .env* (ignored defensively even though this app creates no .env). HOW TO TEST: none needed; it is a static ignore list."
    },
    {
      "path": "README.md",
      "specification": "PURPOSE: human-facing project documentation. CONTENT (English prose, no code changes to behavior): a one-paragraph overview (modern responsive full-stack Student Profile system on Next.js 14 App Router + React 18 TypeScript, Tailwind v3, Prisma over local SQLite; view/add/edit/delete with client-side search and summary metrics; validation centralized in src/lib/validation.ts). Prerequisites: Node.js 18+ and npm; no .env needed. Setup steps in order: npm install; npx prisma generate; npx prisma db push; npm run db:seed (optional); npm run dev; served at http://localhost:3000. A Commands table describing dev/build/start/lint/test/db:push/db:seed. A 'No .env required' note explaining the datasource url is a hardcoded literal, not an env() reference, and nothing reads/parses .env. A Testing section describing the three Vitest surfaces (validation logic, mocked API route handlers, jsdom component a11y) and that styling is verified by build+lint. A Features section covering the four CRUD flows and the deliberate scope difference: summary metrics reflect the full dataset while search filters only the visible cards. HOW TO TEST: documentation only; commands it lists must match package.json."
    },
    {
      "path": "vitest.config.ts",
      "specification": "PURPOSE: configure the three test surfaces across node + jsdom. SIGNATURES: default-export defineConfig({...}) from 'vitest/config'. CONTENT: test.globals = true; test.environment = 'node' (default, for validation + route suites); test.environmentMatchGlobs = [['src/**/*.dom.test.tsx', 'jsdom']] (routes only the component suites to jsdom); test.setupFiles = ['./src/test/setup.ts']; test.include = ['src/**/*.test.ts', 'src/**/*.test.tsx']. resolve.alias '@' -> the src directory computed as new URL('./src', import.meta.url).pathname. EDGE CASES: the '@' alias MUST resolve to the same specifier the handlers import so vi.mock('@/lib/prisma') intercepts the real module; the include glob MUST cover both .test.ts and .test.tsx. HOW TO TEST: npm run test discovers and runs all three suites."
    },
    {
      "path": "src/test/setup.ts",
      "specification": "PURPOSE: shared Vitest setup registering jest-dom matchers. CONTENT: a single side-effect import of '@testing-library/jest-dom' so expect gains toHaveFocus/toBeDisabled/toHaveAttribute/aria checks used by the jsdom suites. EDGE CASES: harmless for the node suites, which never call those matchers. HOW TO TEST: the component suites relying on these matchers pass."
    },
    {
      "path": "prisma/schema.prisma",
      "specification": "PURPOSE: Prisma schema for the Student model over SQLite. CONTENT: generator client { provider = 'prisma-client-js' }. datasource db { provider = 'sqlite'; url = 'file:./dev.db' } — a hardcoded literal, NOT env(). model Student { id Int @id @default(autoincrement()); studentId String @unique; fullName String; email String; major String; gpa Float; createdAt DateTime @default(now()); updatedAt DateTime @updatedAt }. EDGE CASES/CONTRACT: the @unique on studentId is the guarantee behind the API's 409 duplicate contract (Prisma P2002); email is intentionally NOT unique. HOW TO TEST: npx prisma generate then npx prisma db push create prisma/dev.db with a Student table and the unique index."
    },
    {
      "path": "prisma/migrations/migration_lock.toml",
      "specification": "PURPOSE: Prisma migration provider lock. CONTENT: the standard 'do not edit manually' header comment followed by provider = 'sqlite'. MUST NOT: hand-edit. HOW TO TEST: none; it pins the migration provider."
    },
    {
      "path": "prisma/migrations/20260714060056_init/migration.sql",
      "specification": "PURPOSE: committed initial migration history consistent with schema.prisma. CONTENT: a CreateTable 'Student' with columns id INTEGER NOT NULL PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT, studentId TEXT NOT NULL, fullName TEXT NOT NULL, email TEXT NOT NULL, major TEXT NOT NULL, gpa REAL NOT NULL, createdAt DATETIME NOT NULL DEFAULT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, updatedAt DATETIME NOT NULL; and a CreateIndex CREATE UNIQUE INDEX 'Student_studentId_key' ON 'Student'('studentId'). EDGE CASES: a generated artifact; it MUST match schema.prisma exactly. The documented setup uses `prisma db push`, so this folder is retained history rather than the primary bootstrap path. HOW TO TEST: prisma accepts it as valid migration SQL for the sqlite provider."
    },
    {
      "path": "prisma/seed.ts",
      "specification": "PURPOSE: idempotently seed sample students so the dashboard opens non-empty. SIGNATURES: async function main(): Promise<void>. CONTENT: instantiate a PrismaClient; define an array of six students with exact data spanning majors and the full GPA scale (so the emerald/amber/rose thresholds are all exercised): {S1001, Ada Lovelace, ada.lovelace@example.edu, Computer Science, 3.95}, {S1002, Grace Hopper, grace.hopper@example.edu, Mathematics, 3.6}, {S1003, Marie Curie, marie.curie@example.edu, Physics, 2.85}, {S1004, Charles Darwin, charles.darwin@example.edu, Biology, 3.1}, {S1005, John Nash, john.nash@example.edu, Economics, 1.9}, {S1006, Nikola Tesla, nikola.tesla@example.edu, Electrical Engineering, 0.75}. HOW TO IMPLEMENT: in main() loop and prisma.student.upsert({ where: { studentId }, update: student, create: student }) keyed on the unique studentId so re-running updates in place (idempotent), then console.log the seeded count. Chain main().catch(err => { console.error(...); process.exit(1); }).finally(() => prisma.$disconnect()). ERROR HANDLING: a failure logs and exits with code 1; disconnect always runs. HOW TO TEST: run npm run db:seed twice — the second run must not create duplicates."
    },
    {
      "path": "src/lib/prisma.ts",
      "specification": "PURPOSE: a single shared PrismaClient that survives Next dev HMR without exhausting DB connections. SIGNATURES: export const prisma: PrismaClient. HOW TO IMPLEMENT: widen globalThis with a narrow cast to an optional { prismaGlobal?: PrismaClient } slot; set prisma to globalForPrisma.prismaGlobal ?? new PrismaClient(); when process.env.NODE_ENV !== 'production', cache it back onto globalForPrisma.prismaGlobal so subsequent hot reloads reuse it (production processes get a fresh, non-global client). Export prisma as a NAMED export so route handlers import it and tests can replace it via vi.mock('@/lib/prisma'). EDGE CASES: only NODE_ENV is read from process.env; never read other env/secrets. HOW TO TEST: indirectly — the route tests mock this module by its '@/lib/prisma' specifier."
    },
    {
      "path": "src/lib/validation.ts",
      "specification": "PURPOSE: the single source of truth for student field validation, shared verbatim by the client form and both API routes; every function returns null when valid or a stable English message when invalid, and NONE throws. SIGNATURES & EXACT MESSAGES: export type StudentInput = { studentId: string; fullName: string; email: string; major: string; gpa: string | number } (gpa is string|number so the form can hold a string and the API may receive either). export type FieldName = keyof StudentInput. export type FieldErrors = Partial<Record<FieldName, string>>. export const COMMON_MAJORS: string[] = ['Computer Science','Mathematics','Physics','Biology','Business Administration','Economics','Psychology','Mechanical Engineering','Electrical Engineering','English Literature']. validateStudentId(v: string): string | null — trim; if empty return 'Student ID is required'; if length > 32 return 'Student ID must be 32 characters or fewer'; else null. validateFullName(v: string): string | null — trim; if empty return 'Full name is required'; if length > 100 return 'Full name must be 100 characters or fewer'; else null. validateEmail(v: string): string | null — trim; if empty return 'Email is required'; if it fails the pattern ^[^\\s@]+@[^\\s@]+\\.[^\\s@]+$ return 'Enter a valid email address'; else null. validateMajor(v: string): string | null — trim; if empty return 'Major is required'; if length > 80 return 'Major must be 80 characters or fewer'; else null. parseGpa(v: string | number): number | null — if number, take it directly; if string, trim, return null when empty/whitespace, return null when it does NOT match ^-?\\d+(\\.\\d+)?$ (rejecting 0x3/0b11/1e0/abc BEFORE coercion), else Number(trimmed); finally return null unless Number.isFinite (catching NaN/±Infinity), otherwise the number. validateGpa(v: string | number): string | null — FIRST detect empty independently of parsing (string trims to empty, or a number that is NaN) and return 'GPA is required'; then let n = parseGpa(v); if n === null return 'GPA must be a plain decimal number (e.g. 3.75)'; if n < 0 or n > 4 return 'GPA must be between 0.0 and 4.0'; else null. validateStudent(input: StudentInput): FieldErrors — run each field validator and include a key only for failing fields, in order studentId, fullName, email, major, gpa; an empty object means valid. EDGE CASES: distinct GPA messages for empty vs unparsable vs out-of-range so a user who typed something is never told the field is empty; the closed interval [0.0,4.0] includes both boundaries; length caps use String.length after trimming (ASCII-pragmatic). HOW TO TEST: locked by src/lib/validation.test.ts."
    },
    {
      "path": "src/lib/validation.test.ts",
      "specification": "PURPOSE: node-env Vitest suite locking every validator's exact return value and message so the client and API cannot drift. HOW TO IMPLEMENT: declare message constants LOCALLY (mirrored, not imported) so any source message change must be deliberately reflected here. HOW TO TEST (cases): validateStudentId — null for 'S1001'; 'Student ID is required' for '' and '   '; 'Student ID must be 32 characters or fewer' for 33 chars; null at the 32-char boundary. validateFullName — null for 'Ada Lovelace'; required for ''; length message for 101 chars; null at 100. validateEmail — null for 'a@b.co'; required for ''; 'Enter a valid email address' for 'nope', 'a@b', 'a b@c.com', 'a@@b.com'. validateMajor — null for 'Physics'; required for ''; length message for 81; null at 80. parseGpa number branch — returns 3.5 and 0 unchanged; returns null for NaN, Infinity, -Infinity. parseGpa string branch — parses '3.75' -> 3.75 and '0' -> 0; null for '' and '   '; null for 'abc', '0x3', '0b11', '1e0'. validateGpa — null for '0', '4', '2.7'; required for '' and '   '; range message for '-0.1' and '4.1'; the invalid-format message (and explicitly NOT the required message) for 'x', '0x3', '1e0'. validateStudent — {} for a fully valid input; for { studentId:'', fullName:'Ada Lovelace', email:'nope', major:'Physics', gpa:'5' } returns exactly { studentId: required, email: invalid, gpa: range } and omits the valid fields."
    },
    {
      "path": "src/app/api/students/route.ts",
      "specification": "PURPOSE: collection endpoints. SIGNATURES: export const dynamic = 'force-dynamic'; export async function GET(): Promise<NextResponse>; export async function POST(request: Request): Promise<NextResponse>. Import prisma from '@/lib/prisma' and parseGpa/validateStudent/StudentInput from '@/lib/validation' (NextResponse from 'next/server'). HELPERS: a local readString(source: Record<string, unknown>, key: string): string returning the value only when it is a string, else ''. HOW TO IMPLEMENT: GET returns NextResponse.json(await prisma.student.findMany({ orderBy: { createdAt: 'desc' } }), { status: 200 }). POST: (1) try request.json(); on throw return 400 { error: 'Invalid JSON' }; (2) if the parsed value is not a plain non-array object (null/array/string/number) treat body as {} so validators emit the standard required messages; (3) build a StudentInput coercing text fields via readString (missing/non-string -> '') and passing gpa through only when it is a string or number, else ''; (4) errors = validateStudent(input); if it has any keys return 400 { errors }; (5) otherwise prisma.student.create({ data: { studentId/fullName/email/major trimmed, gpa: parseGpa(input.gpa) as number } }) and return 201 with the created student; (6) in catch, if the error carries code 'P2002' return 409 { errors: { studentId: 'A student with this Student ID already exists' } }, otherwise return 500 { error: 'Internal server error' }. ERROR/EDGE CASES: never cache (force-dynamic); validation runs before any DB call; only P2002 maps to 409, all other throws to 500. HOW TO TEST: locked by src/app/api/students/route.test.ts."
    },
    {
      "path": "src/app/api/students/[id]/route.ts",
      "specification": "PURPOSE: item endpoints addressed by the numeric primary key. SIGNATURES: export const dynamic = 'force-dynamic'; export async function PATCH(request: Request, { params }: { params: { id: string } }): Promise<NextResponse>; export async function DELETE(request: Request, { params }: { params: { id: string } }): Promise<Response>. HELPERS: NUMERIC_ID_PATTERN = /^\\d+$/; MAX_ID_DIGITS = 15; notFound() -> NextResponse.json({ error: 'Not found' }, { status: 404 }); parseId(raw: string): number | null — return null unless raw matches NUMERIC_ID_PATTERN, its length <= 15, and Number(raw) is a safe integer > 0; hasErrorCode(error: unknown, code: string): boolean narrowing an object with a matching .code; readString as in the collection route. HOW TO IMPLEMENT: PATCH — parseId(params.id); if null return notFound(); try request.json() else 400 { error: 'Invalid JSON' }; coerce a non-plain-object body to {}; build StudentInput exactly as POST does; run validateStudent and return 400 { errors } if non-empty; else prisma.student.update({ where: { id }, data: trimmed fields + parseGpa(input.gpa) as number }) and return 200; in catch map P2025 -> notFound(), P2002 -> 409 { errors: { studentId: duplicate message } }, else 500 { error: 'Internal server error' }. DELETE — parseId; if null return notFound(); try prisma.student.delete({ where: { id } }) and return new Response(null, { status: 204 }); in catch map P2025 -> notFound(), else 500. ERROR/EDGE CASES: a bad id (non-digit, 0, negative, decimal, hex, exponent, or overlong) never reaches Prisma — it is a non-enumerating 404 that does not leak whether an id maps to a record; the 204 uses a plain Response with a null body (not NextResponse.json). HOW TO TEST: locked by the shared route test file."
    },
    {
      "path": "src/app/api/students/route.test.ts",
      "specification": "PURPOSE: node-env Vitest suite locking the full status-code contract for both routes WITHOUT a database. HOW TO IMPLEMENT: vi.mock('@/lib/prisma', ...) BEFORE importing the handlers, exposing prisma.student with findMany/create/update/delete as vi.fn(); import { GET, POST } from '@/app/api/students/route' and { PATCH, DELETE } from '@/app/api/students/[id]/route'; cast each mocked method to a vi.fn view for typing; define DUPLICATE_MESSAGE = 'A student with this Student ID already exists' and a VALID payload { studentId:'S1', fullName:'Ada', email:'a@b.co', major:'CS', gpa:'3.5' } (pre-trimmed, gpa as string); a makeRequest(method, body) helper that sends a string body verbatim (to exercise malformed JSON) or JSON.stringifies otherwise; a params(id) helper returning { params: { id } }; beforeEach vi.clearAllMocks(). HOW TO TEST (cases): GET -> 200 and body equals the findMany rows. POST -> 201 with the created student AND create called with exactly { data: { studentId:'S1', fullName:'Ada', email:'a@b.co', major:'CS', gpa:3.5 } } (trimmed + numeric); 400 with errors.studentId and errors.email for { ...VALID, studentId:'', email:'nope' } and create not called; 400 { error:'Invalid JSON' } for a '{not json' body with create not called; 409 with errors.studentId === DUPLICATE_MESSAGE when create rejects { code:'P2002' }; 500 for a rejected { code:'PXXXX' }; 500 for a rejected new Error('boom'). PATCH -> 200 for a valid update with update called once; 404 (update not called) for each invalid id in ['abc','0','-1','0x1','1e1','1.0']; 400 with errors.email for a valid id '1' but { ...VALID, email:'nope' } and update not called; 404 { error:'Not found' } when update rejects { code:'P2025' }; 409 with errors.studentId === DUPLICATE_MESSAGE when update rejects { code:'P2002' }. DELETE -> 204 with an empty text() body and delete called once; 404 when delete rejects { code:'P2025' }; 404 for invalid ids ['abc','0x1'] with delete not called. Include a scope note that 401/403 are intentionally out of scope."
    },
    {
      "path": "src/app/globals.css",
      "specification": "PURPOSE: global stylesheet wiring Tailwind layers plus base theme and the mandatory focus strategy. CONTENT: the three directives @tailwind base; @tailwind components; @tailwind utilities. @layer base: html, body { min-height: 100% }. body { min-height: 100vh; background-color: #020617 (slate-950 fallback); background-image: linear-gradient(160deg, #020617 0%, #0b1220 55%, #111a33 100%); background-attachment: fixed; color: #f1f5f9; -webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased; -moz-osx-font-smoothing: grayscale }. A universal focus fallback *:focus-visible { outline: none; box-shadow: 0 0 0 2px #020617, 0 0 0 4px #10b981 } (an inner gap in the page background color and an outer emerald ring following the element radius). input, select, textarea, button { font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 1.5rem } (>=16px so iOS never zooms). @layer components: .card { @apply rounded-2xl border border-white/10 bg-white/5 shadow-lg backdrop-blur } — the reusable frosted-glass surface. NOTE: the *:focus-visible fallback and the components' local focus-visible ring utilities are complementary, not alternatives. HOW TO TEST: verified by build + visual rendering."
    },
    {
      "path": "src/app/layout.tsx",
      "specification": "PURPOSE: root layout loading fonts, metadata, and the global stylesheet. SIGNATURES: export const metadata: Metadata = { title: 'Student Profile System', description: 'Manage student profiles' }; export default function RootLayout({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }). HOW TO IMPLEMENT: import './globals.css'; load Inter({ subsets: ['latin'], variable: '--font-inter' }) and Outfit({ subsets: ['latin'], variable: '--font-outfit' }) from 'next/font/google'; render <html lang='en' className={`${inter.variable} ${outfit.variable}`}> so both CSS variables (mapped in tailwind.config.ts) are available tree-wide, and <body className='font-sans'>{children}</body> defaulting to Inter. HOW TO TEST: build succeeds and the fonts resolve as CSS variables consumed by Tailwind fontFamily."
    },
    {
      "path": "src/app/page.tsx",
      "specification": "PURPOSE: the dashboard home route as a React Server Component that loads students and renders the interactive dashboard. SIGNATURES: export const dynamic = 'force-dynamic'; export default async function Page(). HOW TO IMPLEMENT: no 'use client'; import prisma from '@/lib/prisma' and StudentDashboard from '@/components/StudentDashboard'; await prisma.student.findMany({ orderBy: { createdAt: 'desc' } }); map each row to a plain, fully serializable object matching the client Student shape, converting createdAt/updatedAt with toISOString(); render a <main> shell (centered max-w-6xl, responsive horizontal padding, vertical padding) containing a header (an h2/h1 title 'Student Profile System' in the display font and a muted description paragraph) and <StudentDashboard initialStudents={students} />. EDGE CASES: do NOT special-case the empty list here — pass it through so the dashboard renders its own empty state; force-dynamic keeps every request against live data (client mutations call router.refresh() to re-run this). HOW TO TEST: covered end-to-end by build + the app behavior; no unit test."
    },
    {
      "path": "src/components/StudentDashboard.tsx",
      "specification": "PURPOSE: the top-level 'use client' orchestrator for metrics, search, the card grid, and the CRUD dialogs. SIGNATURES: export default function StudentDashboard({ initialStudents }: { initialStudents: Student[] }) using the client Student shape; imports useMemo/useState, useRouter from 'next/navigation', FieldErrors/StudentInput types from '@/lib/validation', and the SummaryCards/SearchFilter/StudentCard/StudentForm/DeleteDialog components. STATE: query (string); formOpen (boolean); editing (Student|null); deleting (Student|null); submitting (boolean); serverErrors (FieldErrors); actionError (string|null). HOW TO IMPLEMENT: derive filtered via useMemo over [initialStudents, query] applying the search semantics from the global conventions (toLowerCase substring over fullName/major/studentId, empty query -> all). handleAdd sets editing null, clears serverErrors/actionError, opens the form; handleEdit(student) seeds editing, clears errors, opens; handleDeleteRequest(student) clears actionError and sets deleting; closeForm resets formOpen/editing/serverErrors; closeDelete clears deleting. handleSubmit(values: StudentInput): choose url '/api/students/{editing.id}' + method PATCH when editing else '/api/students' + POST; set submitting true, clear actionError; fetch with JSON body; if response.ok -> closeForm() then router.refresh(); else if status is 400 or 409 -> parse the body (guard with .catch(() => ({}))) and setServerErrors(body.errors || {}); else set a generic 'Something went wrong while saving. Please try again.'; catch network -> 'Unable to reach the server. Please try again.'; finally submitting false. handleConfirmDelete: if no deleting target return; set submitting true; DELETE '/api/students/{target.id}'; ok -> closeDelete() then router.refresh(); else 'Unable to delete this student. Please try again.'; catch network message; finally submitting false. RENDER: SummaryCards receives initialStudents UNTOUCHED (full-dataset metrics); SearchFilter is a controlled pair (query/setQuery) plus onAdd; an actionError banner with role='alert' when set (for non-field failures the dialogs cannot express); then three exclusive states — if initialStudents.length === 0 an empty state ('No students yet' + prompt), else if filtered.length === 0 a no-match state referencing the trimmed query, else a responsive grid (1/2/3 columns at base/sm/lg) of StudentCard wrapped in fade-in-up divs with a staggered animationDelay of index*60ms, keyed by student.id. Mount StudentForm only while formOpen (open, initial=editing, serverErrors, submitting, onSubmit=handleSubmit, onClose=closeForm) and DeleteDialog only while deleting is set (open, student=deleting, submitting, onConfirm=handleConfirmDelete, onCancel=closeDelete). EDGE CASES: metrics never reflect the filter; dialogs are conditionally mounted so their focus effects run cleanly. HOW TO TEST: its child dialogs are covered by the jsdom suites; the dashboard itself is verified via build + manual flow."
    },
    {
      "path": "src/components/SummaryCards.tsx",
      "specification": "PURPOSE: pure presentational summary metrics over the full dataset (no 'use client' directive, no hooks/state — it is imported into the client tree). SIGNATURES: export default function SummaryCards({ students }: { students: Student[] }) using the client Student shape; internal helpers computeAverageGpa(students: Student[]): string and computeTopMajor(students: Student[]): string, and an internal SummaryCard({ label, value, icon, gradient }) presentational subcomponent. HOW TO IMPLEMENT: total = students.length. computeAverageGpa: '—' when empty; otherwise Math.round((sum/total)*100)/100 then .toFixed(2). computeTopMajor: count majors in a Map (insertion order preserved), track the highest count, keep the first-seen major on ties, return '—' when empty. Render a <section aria-label='Summary metrics'> as a responsive grid (1/2/3 cols) of three SummaryCard tiles: Total Students (Users icon, brand gradient), Average GPA (GraduationCap icon, emerald gradient), Top Major (TrendingUp icon, amber gradient), each with the value in the display font, a subtle hover lift, and lucide icons marked aria-hidden. EDGE CASES: all aggregates guard the empty list so there is never a division by zero or NaN (they degrade to '0'/'—'). HOW TO TEST: verified via build; behavior is deterministic per the documented aggregate rules."
    },
    {
      "path": "src/components/SearchFilter.tsx",
      "specification": "PURPOSE: 'use client' controlled header row combining the search box and the Add action. SIGNATURES: export default function SearchFilter({ value, onChange, onAdd }: { value: string; onChange: (v: string) => void; onAdd: () => void }); imports Plus and Search from 'lucide-react'. HOW IMPLEMENT: a flex container that stacks vertically on mobile and becomes a row from sm up; the search field grows to fill the row. Include a visually hidden <label htmlFor> ('Search students by name, major, or student ID') bound to a stable input id; a decorative leading Search icon marked aria-hidden and pointer-events-none; a controlled <input type='search'> wired to value/onChange with a placeholder ('Search by name, major, or ID…'), >=48px min height, and focus-visible ring utilities. The Add button is a real <button type='button' onClick={onAdd}> with a gradient fill, a leading Plus icon (aria-hidden), the text 'Add Student', >=48px min height, and a focus-visible ring. EDGE CASES: holds no local state; the search semantics live in the parent. HOW TO TEST: verified via build; interaction is exercised through the dashboard."
    },
    {
      "path": "src/components/StudentCard.tsx",
      "specification": "PURPOSE: 'use client' presentation of one student as a frosted-glass card with edit/delete actions. SIGNATURES: export default function StudentCard({ student, onEdit, onDelete }: { student: Student; onEdit: (s: Student) => void; onDelete: (s: Student) => void }) using the client Student shape; internal gpaTheme(gpa: number): { dot: string; pill: string }; imports Pencil and Trash2 from 'lucide-react'. HOW IMPLEMENT: gpaTheme returns emerald classes when gpa >= 3.5, amber when gpa >= 2.5, else rose (a dot color plus a matching translucent bordered pill). Render an <article> on the shared .card surface with a hover scale/shadow transition and flex-col layout. Header: the full name in the display font (truncate), the studentId as a small muted badge, and two icon-only buttons on the right — Edit (Pencil) calling onEdit(student) and Delete (Trash2) calling onDelete(student) — each a 48px square target with a focus-visible ring and an aria-label naming the student (e.g. 'Edit {fullName}', 'Delete {fullName}') since the icon carries no text. Below: the email in a truncating paragraph with a title attribute. Footer (pushed to the bottom): a major chip (truncating) and the GPA pill rendering a colored dot (aria-hidden) plus 'GPA {student.gpa.toFixed(2)}' in the display font. EDGE CASES: long email/major/name must truncate rather than overflow. HOW TO TEST: verified via build; the GPA color thresholds match the global convention."
    },
    {
      "path": "src/components/StudentForm.tsx",
      "specification": "PURPOSE: 'use client' accessible add/edit modal backing both flows (add when initial is null, edit when initial is a student). SIGNATURES: export default function StudentForm({ open, initial, serverErrors, submitting, onSubmit, onClose }: { open: boolean; initial: Student | null; serverErrors: FieldErrors; submitting: boolean; onSubmit: (values: StudentInput) => void; onClose: () => void }); imports the per-field validators, validateStudent, COMMON_MAJORS, and FieldErrors/FieldName/StudentInput from '@/lib/validation'. INTERNAL CONSTANTS: FormValues = Record<FieldName, string>; FIELD_ORDER = ['studentId','fullName','email','major','gpa']; a VALIDATORS map from field name to its single-value validator; ID_PREFIX 'student-form'; DATALIST_ID and TITLE_ID derived from it; the shared FOCUSABLE_SELECTOR; blankValues() and valuesFromStudent(student) (gpa via String(...)). STATE/REFS: values (init from initial or blank), touched (Set<FieldName>), errors (FieldErrors); panelRef (dialog panel) and inputRefs (per-field). EFFECTS: (1) on mount capture document.activeElement and restore focus to it on unmount (focus-restore); (2) on [open, initial] reset values/touched/errors so add starts blank and edit seeds from the student; (3) on [serverErrors] merge any incoming field errors onto the same slots and mark those fields touched; (4) on [open] move focus to the Student ID input. HANDLERS: handleChange(field, value) sets the value and deletes that field's error (clear-on-input); handleBlur(field) marks it touched and sets/clears its error via VALIDATORS[field] (validate-on-blur); handleSubmit(event) preventDefault, run validateStudent(values), and if any errors set them, mark ALL fields touched, focus the first invalid field in FIELD_ORDER, and do NOT call onSubmit — otherwise call onSubmit({ ...values }) (GPA stays a string; the server/parseGpa converts it); handleKeyDown implements Escape -> preventDefault + onClose and the Tab/Shift+Tab focus trap wrapping at both ends over FOCUSABLE_SELECTOR scoped to panelRef; handleOverlayClick closes when the click target is the overlay itself. RENDER: return null when !open. A fixed inset overlay (z-50, dim + backdrop blur, onClick=handleOverlayClick) containing the panel (role='dialog', aria-modal='true', aria-labelledby=TITLE_ID, onKeyDown=handleKeyDown, on the .card surface). An h2 heading id=TITLE_ID reading 'Add student' or 'Edit student'. A <form noValidate onSubmit={handleSubmit}> mapping FIELD_ORDER to fields, each with: a <label htmlFor> above the control (labels 'Student ID','Full Name','Email','Major','GPA'); an <input id ref name value onChange onBlur>; aria-invalid='true' and aria-describedby={errorId} only when that field has an error; type='number' for gpa (inputMode='decimal', step='0.1', min='0', max='4'), type='email' for email, else 'text'; list=DATALIST_ID on the major field plus a sibling <datalist> populated from COMMON_MAJORS; a <p id={errorId}> rendering the message when invalid; controls are >=48px tall with focus-visible rings and a rose border when invalid. Footer buttons: a Cancel <button type='button' onClick={onClose}> and a submit <button type='submit' disabled={submitting}> whose label is 'Save changes' when editing else 'Add student'. EDGE CASES: noValidate makes the aria messages the single source of truth; the focusable set is exactly the five inputs plus Cancel and Submit (datalist options are not focusable), so first=Student ID input and last=submit button for the trap. HOW TO TEST: locked by src/components/StudentForm.dom.test.tsx."
    },
    {
      "path": "src/components/StudentForm.dom.test.tsx",
      "specification": "PURPOSE: jsdom Vitest suite locking StudentForm's hand-written a11y behaviors. HOW TO IMPLEMENT: mirror the exact FOCUSABLE_SELECTOR string; define a fully valid input VALID = { studentId:'S1001', fullName:'Ada Lovelace', email:'a@b.co', major:'Computer Science', gpa:'3.9' }; a Harness component owning open state with a real trigger <button>Open form</button> that renders StudentForm (initial null, serverErrors {}, submitting false, onClose closing state + calling the spy); an openForm() helper that renders the harness, clicks the trigger, awaits findByRole('dialog'), and returns { user, onSubmit, onClose, trigger, dialog }; a focusables(dialog) helper querying the selector. HOW TO TEST (cases): (1) after open, the Student ID field has focus (await waitFor). (2) typing 'nope' into Email then tabbing away shows 'Enter a valid email address', sets aria-invalid='true', and wires aria-describedby to an element containing that message. (3) after showing that error, typing another character clears the message and removes aria-invalid. (4) focusing the last focusable control and pressing Tab wraps focus to the first. (5) focusing the first and pressing Shift+Tab wraps to the last. (6) pressing Escape calls onClose once. (7) after Escape, focus returns to the trigger (await waitFor). (8) clicking the submit button ('Add student') on an empty form does NOT call onSubmit and surfaces all five required messages ('Student ID is required','Full name is required','Email is required','Major is required','GPA is required'); then filling every field with VALID and submitting calls onSubmit exactly once with VALID (gpa still the string '3.9')."
    },
    {
      "path": "src/components/DeleteDialog.tsx",
      "specification": "PURPOSE: 'use client' confirmation modal (ARIA alertdialog) guarding student deletion. SIGNATURES: export default function DeleteDialog({ open, student, submitting, onConfirm, onCancel }: { open: boolean; student: Student | null; submitting: boolean; onConfirm: () => void; onCancel: () => void }); imports AlertTriangle from 'lucide-react'. INTERNAL: the shared FOCUSABLE_SELECTOR; TITLE_ID and BODY_ID constants; panelRef and cancelRef. EFFECT: on mount capture document.activeElement as the trigger, focus cancelRef (the safe default), and on unmount restore focus to the trigger if it is still a connected focusable element. EARLY RETURN: render null when !open || !student. HANDLERS: getFocusable() collects FOCUSABLE_SELECTOR matches inside panelRef in DOM order; handleKeyDown implements Escape -> preventDefault + onCancel and the Tab/Shift+Tab trap wrapping at both ends (if the focusable set is empty, preventDefault to keep focus in the dialog); handleOverlayClick (bound to onMouseDown on the overlay) calls onCancel only when target === currentTarget. RENDER: a fixed inset overlay (z-50, dim + backdrop blur, onMouseDown=handleOverlayClick) containing the panel (role='alertdialog', aria-modal='true', aria-labelledby=TITLE_ID, aria-describedby=BODY_ID, onKeyDown=handleKeyDown, on the .card surface). Inside: a rose-tinted warning badge with an AlertTriangle icon (aria-hidden); an h2 id=TITLE_ID 'Delete {student.fullName}?'; a body <p id=BODY_ID> naming the student and studentId and warning the action is permanent. Footer: a Cancel <button ref={cancelRef} type='button' onClick={onCancel}> and a destructive Delete <button type='button' onClick={onConfirm} disabled={submitting}> whose label is 'Deleting…' when submitting else 'Delete'; both are >=48px with focus-visible rings. EDGE CASES: the disabled Delete button is excluded from the focusable set while submitting, so the trap never lands on it. HOW TO TEST: locked by src/components/DeleteDialog.dom.test.tsx."
    },
    {
      "path": "src/components/DeleteDialog.dom.test.tsx",
      "specification": "PURPOSE: jsdom Vitest suite locking DeleteDialog's a11y behaviors. HOW TO IMPLEMENT: define a SAMPLE_STUDENT of the client Student shape; a renderDialog(overrides) helper rendering the dialog open with fresh onConfirm/onCancel spies (and an optional submitting flag); a Harness({ onCancel }) with a real trigger button and open state whose DeleteDialog onCancel calls the spy AND closes (unmounts), mirroring the dashboard. HOW TO TEST (cases): focus moves to the Cancel button on open; pressing Escape calls onCancel once; clicking the overlay backdrop (the panel's parentElement, obtained from getByRole('alertdialog')) calls onCancel once; clicking Delete calls onConfirm exactly once; the focus trap wraps both ends (from the Delete button Tab wraps to Cancel; from Cancel Shift+Tab wraps to Delete); after opening from the real trigger and pressing Escape, onCancel fires and focus is restored to the trigger; when submitting is true the Delete button (accessible name matching /deleting/i) is disabled."
    }
  ]
}
```